\begin{proof}
  Let $g, h\in S_n$ be given. Given the inclusion $S_k \sub S_n$ noted above, we have
\[ S_k g = S_k h \quad \Leftrightarrow\quad \forall i \in \{k+1, \ldots, n\} . (i) \cdot g = (i) \cdot h \]
Hence the function $S_n \to X^0$ defined by $g \mapsto ((k+1) \cdot g), \ldots, (n) \cdot g)$ lifts
to the quotient and defines a bijection $S_n / S_k \to X^0$.

It remains sto see that $X^1$ is the set of edges. Let $a = (a_{k+1}, \ldots, a_n) \in X^0$.
We have $i \cdot g = a_i$ for $k+1 \le i \le n$ and for any $g$ in the equivalence class represented by $a$.
We need to calculate the right coset in $S_n / S_k$ of $gs$ for $s \in S$.

Let $\ell$ be given with $1 \le \ell \le n-1$ and let $s$ be the transposition $(\ell, \ell+1)$.
There are three cases:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Neither $\ell$ nor $\ell+1$ are in the set of coordinates of $a$
\item One of the two is in the set of coordinates of $a$
\item Both are in set of coordinates of $a$
\end{enumerate}
We treat these cases as follows.
\begin{enumerate}
\item We have
\[ ((i)\cdot g)\cdot s = a_i \cdot s = a_i \]
because $a_i \ne \ell, \ell+1$ for $i \in [k+1, n]$. There is no edge because $g$ and $gs$ are in the same equivalence class.
\item Let $j \in [k+1, n]$ be given such that $a_j = \ell$. The equivalence class of $g$ is represented by
\[ [g] = (a_{k+1}, \ldots a_{j-1}, \ell, a_{j+1}, \ldots, a_n)\]
and for $h \in [k+1,n]$ with $h\ne j$ we have
\[(h)\cdot(gs) = a_h\]
because then $a_h \ne \ell, \ell+1$. For $j$ we get
\[ (j) \cdot (gs) = \ell \cdot s = \ell+1\]
The class of $gs$ is represented by the vertex $(a_{k+1}, \ldots, a_{j-1}, \ell+1, a_{j+1}, \ldots, a_n)$
and we have an edge of type $X^1_1$. The case of $a_j = \ell + 1$ is analogous.
\item Let $i,j\in [k+1, n]$ such that $a_i = \ell$ and $a_j = \ell + 1$. For $h \in [k+1,n]$ with
$h \not\in \{i,j\}$, we have
\[(h) \cdot(gs) = a_h\]
For $i$ and $j$ we have
\[(i)\cdot(gs) = \ell \cdot s = \ell + 1 \qquad (j)\cdot(gs) = (\ell+1)\cdot s = \ell\]
so we have an edge of type $X^1_2$. \cqed
\end{enumerate}
\end{proof}

{\bf Remark.} There are $n\choose k$ ``obvious'' embeddings (up to an
interior automorphism of $S_k$) of $S_k$ into $S_n$. These correspond
to a choice of subset of $k$ of the $n$ elements on which $S_k$
acts in the evident way, and which acts trivially on the other elements.
For each of these embeddings the graph
$X(S_k \sub S_n, S)$ is isomorphic (as an abstract graph) to the graph
described by Proposition~\ref{prop.schreier}. This can be seen by
taking the above proof and modifying it to consider instead the restriction
of $S_k g$ to the set $\{1, \ldots, \hat i_1, \ldots, \hat i_k, \ldots, n\}$
 where $\{i_1, \ldots, i_k\}$ is the set of elements
on which $S_k$ acts non-trivially.

Here, as a corollary, is a description of the Cayley graph $X(S_n, S)$:

\begin{proposition}
The Cayley graph $X(S_n, S)$ is given by:
\[X^0 = \{(a_1, \ldots, a_n) \in [1,n]^n \st i \ne j \imp a_i \ne a_j\}\]
\[X^1 = \{\{a,b\} \subseteq X^0 \st d(a, b) = \sqrt{2}\}\]
\end{proposition}

\begin{proof}
There are no edges of type $X^1_1$ in the sense of the preceding proposition, and two vertices of $X(S_n, S)$ are connected
by an edge of type $X^1_2$ iff the Euclidean distance between them is $\sqrt{2}$.
  \cqed
\end{proof}
